{{mergefrom|London Society of West India Planters and Merchants|discuss=Talk:West India Committee#Merger proposal|date=May 2018}}
{{Infobox organization | name = West India Committee | former name = | image = | image_border = | size = <!-- default 200px --> | alt = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] --> | caption = | map = | msize = <!-- map size, optional, default 250px --> | malt = <!-- map alt text --> | mcaption = | map2 = | abbreviation = | motto = | predecessor = | successor = | formation = 1775 | founder = <!-- or | founders = --> | extinction = <!-- {{End date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | merger = | merged = | type = [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]] | status = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc --> | purpose = <!-- focus as e.g. humanitarian, peacekeeping, etc --> | professional_title = <!-- for professional associations --> | headquarters = | location = | coords = <!-- Coordinates of location using {{Coord}} --> | region_served = | services = | membership = | language = | general = <!-- Secretary General --> | leader_title = | leader_name = | leader_title2 = | leader_name2 = | leader_title3 = | leader_name3 = | leader_title4 = | leader_name4 = | key_people = | main_organ = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc --> | parent_organization = <!-- if one --> | subsidiaries = | affiliations = | budget = | num_staff = | num_volunteers= | slogan = | website = {{url|http://www.westindiacommittee.org/}} | remarks = | footnotes = }} The '''West India Committee''', later also known as '''The Committee to the West Indies''' was an English charity formed out of the [[London Society of West India Planters and Merchants]], established in 1780 as a lobby group for British-based merchants and absentee [[plantocracy|plantation owners]] with business interests in the Caribbean and which later became a group promoting Caribbean businesses to the world's major markets.
==History== The principal commodities were [[cane sugar]], [[rum]], [[mahogany]], other softwood, spices and tropical produce, early on largely confined to types which would last a long transatlantic voyage such as [[coffee]], nuts and desiccated coconut but later expanded to include tropical fruits in general.
In 1904, the committee received a (royal) charter of incorporation at the initiative of the British government. It later acquired charitable status and established two subsidiary bodies: *The Caribbean Council for Europe (CCE) *The Caribbean Trade Advisory Group (Caritag).<ref>{{cite book|title=A Brief History of the West India Committee |first=Douglas |last=Hall |publisher=Caribbean University Press |date= 1971 |isbn= 0854740007 }}</ref><ref>West India Committee: Official Archives, 1899–1998</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charity-commission.gov.uk/ |title=Charity number 258545 |publisher=Charity Commission}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20110810/lead/lead91.html |title=West India Committee renews focus on Jamaica |newspaper=Jamaica Gleaner |date=2011-08-10 |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westindiacommittee.org/ |title=Welcome to |publisher=West India Committee |date= |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref>
Among its records are for example eight collections of Caribbean and English newspapers 1761–1846, reports of the Acting Committee to the Half-Yearly Meeting of the Standing Committee of West India Planters and Merchants, 1878–1883 and albums of photographs and press cuttings on the [[1907 Kingston earthquake]] in Jamaica, a country that was a major subject of its promotion work.<ref name=a>{{cite web|url=http://archiveshub.ac.uk/data/gb0101-ics96.txt |title=West India Committee: Acquired Papers, 1750–1988}}</ref>
==Staff== From at least 1915–1929<ref name=a/> its Secretary was Sir Algernon Edward Aspinall who in the name of his committee published geographical guides to [[Guyana]] and the British Caribbean, such as a 1907 [[Stanford's Guides|Stanford's Guide]]: ''Pocket Guide to the West Indies'' and ''The Handbook of the British West Indies, British Guiana and [[British Honduras]]'' (1929). The Chief Executive is [[Blondel Cluff]] CBE, who is also the [[Anguilla]] government’s representative in the United Kingdom. <ref>{{cite news |title=Cluff in Anguilla for opening of maternity ward at hospital |url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/82878-cluff-in-anguilla-for-opening-of-maternity-ward-at-hospital |accessdate=29 November 2018 |publisher=Daily Herald |date=21 November 2018}}</ref>
